<br>
What I plan on doing is start the story off with a woman who is sitting down wiriting a poem. (this takes place in feudal Japan. Guess you noticed by now I'm in love with Japan.) She doesn't have ANY relevance to the story besides the fact that she is the one who is writing it (She acts as the narrator). Every time I write a chapter I'll close it with a poem, which is when she is writing. I can't explain it perfectly, but I'm sure you get the idea. This is probably the first original idea I've had since yet.<br>
So the deal is that she acts as the narrator, and the poems at the end of each chapter are hers.<br>
<br>
Here is the main story. (I rewrote it, so It's much neater, and I also added some new things to it. I also took away one character, the ninja guy, and made the necro-priest more important to the story.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Characters:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Mamoru-</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> The main character. He has lived a rugged life ever since his father’s school was taken over, and his brother and father were killed. He bears a scar across his chest and face, which are reminders from that day.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Iaka-</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> Iaka is a man who’s in ties with the Yakuza, and other dirty businesses. He is a ronin who plans to dominate all other schools in Japan.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Kazuma-</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> A former Shinto priest who was stripped of his priesthood for practicing the black arts and banished from his village. He came to Iaka, claiming that he could help take down Mamoru (which is so true, but not in the way Iaka would want <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   ). Kazuma's true intentions are to destroy Iaka, and resurrect Shosetsu so he can watch Shosetsu kill Mamoru. He actually wants Mamoru dead, because Mamoru was hired to kill Kazuma once, but failed.<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Keiko-</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> Keiko’s father had a large debt to pay off, and so he borrowed money from Iaka with the collateral being Keiko. When it was time for Iaka to collect the girl (since Keiko's father didn't pay him back), Keiko’s father sent Keiko away with all of his money. Iaka kills Keiko’s father, and is now after his collateral. Keiko has a hefty amount of money, and plans on using it for protection from Iaka, so she purchases the services of Mamoru.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Shosetsu-</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> Mamoru’s brother. He is the true antagonist. His skill with the sword far surpasses Mamoru. He had died many years beforehand, but was resurrected by Kazuma. He wishes to defeat his brother and prove that the sword is meant to kill.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Natsumi-</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> A female bounty hunter that is after Mamoru’s head. She is hired by Iaka, but soon changes her opinion on what’s more important: Friendship or money? She looks back on who is the true criminal, and decides to fight Iaka with Mamoru and Keiko.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Sword Smith-</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> So far, no name has been given to him. He is a lone sword smith who has very few customers. Mamoru comes up to him with a drastic request. Create me a rival sword! This same sword smith created Mamoru’s father’s treasured sword, which was missing from the burial ground of Shosetsu and his father (Shosetsu took the sword. He has always desired that sword). Now Mamoru needs a sword of equal strength to battle Shosetsu!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Basic Story:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Mamoru is a killer for hire. He does any odd job for the right price. One day while in a bar, Keiko comes up to him and asks for a proposition. Here’s the deal: Mamoru has to protect this girl from a group of guys who are after her. Mamoru says that despite his name (which means “protect”) he isn’t the type of person to do “Yojimbo” (bodyguard) jobs. He demands a hefty sum, knowing well that she couldn’t possibly have that kind of money. Oddly enough, she pays him, and Mamoru begins his first job as a bodyguard. (He doesn’t accept all of the money though, just half of it, after realizing how serious she was.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Background:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Mamoru was the son of a great swordsman who created a school to teach his sword art to those who understand the concepts behind what a sword really is: an instrument of murder. Mamoru’s father had two children. Shosetsu was the first born, and then came Mamoru. One day, Iaka came out of nowhere and demanded that Mamoru’s father hand over the dojo's certificate of liscene. Shosetsu and Mamoru fight them alongside their father to protect the dojo, and each claimed a great number of men. Mamoru killed ten of Iaka’s men, and Shosetsu killed the greater number of twenty. Even though they fought hard, it was still not enough, as Shosetsu and Mamoru’s father were killed. Mamoru was wounded across the face and chest, and taken for dead. Mamoru hung on to life, and managed to pull through. He now wishes to avenge his brother and father’s deaths by defeating Iaka and his people one day.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Sub Plot:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
After Mamoru accepts the Job from Keiko, a mysterious man shows up in front of Iaka. He was the fallen priest Kazuma, claiming that he can help kill Mamoru. It was his intention to resurrect Shosetsu and to use him to take down Iaka and use his dojo to boost Shosetsu’s power. Kazuma is actually loyal to Shosetsu. Iaka did not know this, of course. Shosetsu plans on killing his brother. He wants to prove to Mamoru that the sword is meant for killing. Mamoru wants to prove that it isn’t, and that father was wrong. <br>
Shosetsu was a sick individual, who’s lust for power while alive, drove him to love the art of killing all a little too much. His father taught him that the sword is used to kill. It was when he was four years old that these words were carved in stone into the mind of Shosetsu, but his father had an epiphany later on. His father knew that the sword is meant for murder, but that sounded to be far too crude, and came to the assumption that one must kill in order to protect. He names his second son Mamoru because of this. Shosetsu was beyond the point of changing his ways, using his skill to kill for pleasure. He would kill animals he found in the woods, and later killed his first man at age 16 out of pure rage. His father’s immature principle of “the sword is meant to kill” had twisted Shosetsu into a bitter person who loved to kill. Once Kazuma brings Shosetsu back to life, he addresses him as “master”, and tells him of his plan. Shosetsu is reluctant to go along with it at first, but is persuaded by Kazuma. Shosetsu goes over to his father’s grave and robs the Dairyoku from the grave, which was his father’s great sword with the strength of fifty men. Shosetsu will use this sword to kill his brother.<br>
